Chapter 14: The Supreme Tao or the One has Physical and Metaphysical Dimensions 1 We look at it, and we do not see it, and we name it &lsquo;the Uniformity.&rsquo;
We listen to it, and we do not hear it, and we name it &lsquo;the Inaudible.&rsquo;
We try to grasp it, and do not get hold of it, and we name it &lsquo;the Subtle.&rsquo;
With these three qualities, it cannot be made the subject of description; and hence we blend them together and obtain &lsquo;The One&rsquo;.

Chapter 57: The State Should Have Concise but Efficient Laws 1 A state may be ruled by measures of correction. Weapons of war may be used with crafty dexterity. But the kingdom is made one&rsquo;s own only by freedom from action and purpose.
2 The multiplication of prohibitive laws increases the poverty of the people.
The more implements to add to their profit that the people have, the greater disorder is there in the state and clan;

WHEN there happened to be several accusers, they were obliged to agree among themselves that the action might be carried on by a single prosecutor;
If they could not agree, the person before whom the action was brought, appointed one of them to prosecute the quarrel.  When a gentleman challenged a villain, he was obliged to present himself on foot with buckler and baston;
But if he came on horseback, and armed like a gentleman, they took his horse and his arms from him; and stripping him to his shirt, they compelled him to fight in that condition with the villain.

14 Wages vary with the constancy or inconstancy of employment.
15 &ldquo;Employment is much more constant in some trades than in others.&rdquo;
In most manufactures, a journeyman may be sure of employment almost every day. A mason or bricklayer, on the contrary, cannot work in bad weather. His employment depends on the calls of his customers. He frequently has no work. His earnings must maintain him while he is idle and compensate his anxiety and despondence.

